      <hedline>
        <hl1>Gas Pump Woes?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Charles Komanoff letter points out that gas price increase will cost Denver couple, mentioned in June 1 article, only 75 cents more per week to deliver meals to homebound elderly people; says higher energy levies are essential to end US overconsumption of fossil fuels</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Many Feeling Pinch After Newest Surge in U.S. Fuel Prices'' (front page, June 1):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Many Feeling Pinch After Newest Surge in U.S. Fuel Prices'' (front page, June 1):</p>
        <p>You report that a Denver-area couple may be forced by rising gasoline prices to give up their weekly 30-mile trip delivering meals to housebound older people.</p>
        <p>A typical car averaging 20 miles per gallon requires a gallon and a half for the trip. With the price of gas up by about 50 cents a gallon from a year ago, the drive now costs the couple an additional 75 cents.</p>
        <p>Higher energy taxes are indispensable for ending America's overconsumption of fossil fuels. Overplaying the damage from higher fuel costs makes it harder to enact them.</p>
        <p>CHARLES KOMANOFF  New York, June 2, 2004</p>
        <p>The writer is an economic consultant to environmental groups.</p>
      </block>
